README.md
     1‚Üí# The only accessible & unstyled & full featured Input OTP component in the Web. ‚Ä¶
     3‚Üí### OTP Input for React üîê by [@guilhermerodz](https://twitter.com/guilherme_rodz)
    18‚Üíhttps://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/753751f5-eda8-4145-a4b9-7ef51ca5e453
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí## Usage
    22‚Üí```bash
    23‚Üínpm install input-otp
    24‚Üí```
    25‚Üí
    26‚ÜíThen import the component.
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí```diff
    29‚Üí+'use client'
    30‚Üí+import { OTPInput } from 'input-otp'
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üífunction MyForm() {
    33‚Üí  return <form>
    34‚Üí+   <OTPInput maxLength={6} render={({slots})  => (...)} />
    35‚Üí  </form>
    36‚Üí}
    37‚Üí```
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí## Default example
    41‚ÜíThe example below uses `tailwindcss` `@shadcn/ui` `tailwind-merge` `clsx`:
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí```tsx
    44‚Üí'use client'
    45‚Üíimport { OTPInput, SlotProps } from 'input-otp'
    46‚Üí<OTPInput
    47‚Üí  maxLength={6}
    48‚Üí  containerClassName="group flex items-center has-[:disabled]:opacity-30"
    49‚Üí  render={({ slots }) => (
    50‚Üí    <>
    51‚Üí      <div className="flex">
    52‚Üí        {slots.slice(0, 3).map((slot, idx) => (
    53‚Üí          <Slot key={idx} {...slot} />
    54‚Üí        ))}
    55‚Üí      </div>
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí      <FakeDash />
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üí      <div className="flex">
    60‚Üí        {slots.slice(3).map((slot, idx) => (
    61‚Üí          <Slot key={idx} {...slot} />
    62‚Üí        ))}
    63‚Üí      </div>
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   136‚Üí## How it works
   138‚ÜíThere's currently no native OTP/2FA/MFA input in HTML, which means people are either going with 1. a simple input design or 2. custom designs like this one.
   139‚ÜíThis library works by rendering an invisible input as a sibling of the slots, contained by a `relative`ly positioned parent (the container root called _OTPInput_).
   140‚Üí
   141‚Üí## Features
   143‚ÜíThis is the most complete OTP input on the web. It's fully featured 
   144‚Üí
   145‚Üí<details>
   146‚Üí<summary>Supports iOS + Android copy-paste-cut</summary>
   147‚Üí
   148‚Üíhttps://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bdbdc96a-23da-4e89-bff8-990e6a1c4c23
   149‚Üí
   150‚Üí</details>
   151‚Üí
   152‚Üí<details>
   153‚Üí<summary>Automatic OTP code retrieval from transport (e.g SMS)</summary>
   154‚Üí
   155‚ÜíBy default, this input uses `autocomplete='one-time-code'` and it works as it's a single input. 
   156‚Üí
   157‚Üíhttps://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/5705dac6-9159-443b-9c27-b52e93c60ea8
   158‚Üí
   159‚Üí</details>
   160‚Üí
   161‚Üí<details>
   162‚Üí<summary>Supports screen readers (a11y)</summary>
   163‚Üí
   164‚ÜíStripe was my first inspiration to build this library.
   165‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   198‚Üí### Auto tracks if the input has space in the right side for the badge
   200‚Üíhttps://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bf01af88-1f82-463e-adf4-54a737a92f59
   201‚Üí
   202‚Üí</details>
   203‚Üí
   204‚Üí## API Reference
   206‚Üí### OTPInput
   208‚ÜíThe root container. Define settings for the input via props. Then, use the `render` prop to create the slots.
   209‚Üí
   210‚Üí#### Props
   212‚Üí```ts
   213‚Üítype OTPInputProps = {
   214‚Üí  // The number of slots
   215‚Üí  maxLength: number
   216‚Üí
   217‚Üí  // Render function creating the slots
   218‚Üí  render: (props: RenderProps) => React.ReactElement
   219‚Üí  // PS: Render prop is mandatory, except in cases
   220‚Üí  // you'd like to consume the original Context API.
   221‚Üí  // (search for Context in this docs)
   222‚Üí
   223‚Üí  // The class name for the root container
   224‚Üí  containerClassName?: string
   225‚Üí
   226‚Üí  // Value state controlling the input
   227‚Üí  value?: string
   228‚Üí  // Setter for the controlled value (or callback for uncontrolled value)
   229‚Üí  onChange?: (newValue: string) => unknown
   230‚Üí
   231‚Üí  // Callback when the input is complete
   232‚Üí  onComplete?: (...args: any[]) => unknown
   233‚Üí
   234‚Üí  // Where is the text located within the input
   235‚Üí  // Affects click-holding or long-press behavior
   236‚Üí  // Default: 'left'
   237‚Üí  textAlign?: 'left' | 'center' | 'right'
   238‚Üí
   239‚Üí  // Virtual keyboard appearance on mobile
   240‚Üí  // Default: 'numeric'
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   293‚Üí## Examples
   298‚Üí```tsx
   299‚Üíexport default function Page() {
   300‚Üí  const formRef = useRef<HTMLFormElement>(null)
   301‚Üí  const buttonRef = useRef<HTMLButtonElement>(null)
   302‚Üí
   303‚Üí  return (
   304‚Üí    <form ref={formRef}>
   305‚Üí      <OTPInput
   306‚Üí        // ... automatically submit the form
   307‚Üí        onComplete={() => formRef.current?.submit()}
   308‚Üí        // ... or focus the button like as you wish
   309‚Üí        onComplete={() => buttonRef.current?.focus()}
   310‚Üí      />
   311‚Üí
   312‚Üí      <button ref={buttonRef}>Submit</button>
   313‚Üí    </form>
   314‚Üí  )
   315‚Üí}
   316‚Üí```
   317‚Üí</details>
   318‚Üí
   319‚Üí<details>
   320‚Üí<summary>Automatically focus the input when the page loads</summary>
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   377‚Üí## Caveats
   382‚ÜíBy default, `input-otp` handles password managers for you.
   383‚ÜíThe password manager badges should be automatically shifted to the right side.
   384‚Üí
   385‚ÜíHowever, if you still want to block password managers, please disable the `pushPasswordManagerStrategy` and then manually block each PWM.
   386‚Üí
   387‚Üí```diff
   388‚Üí<OTPInput
   389‚Üí  // First, disable library's built-in strategy
   390‚Üí  // for shifting badges automatically
   391‚Üí- pushPasswordManagerStrategy="increase-width"
   392‚Üí+ pushPasswordManagerStrategy="none"
   393‚Üí  // Then, manually add specifics attributes
   394‚Üí  // your password manager docs
   395‚Üí  // Example: block LastPass
   396‚Üí+ data-lpignore="true" 
   397‚Üí  // Example: block 1Password
   398‚Üí+ data-1p-ignore="true"
   399‚Üí/>
   400‚Üí```
   401‚Üí</details>
   402‚Üí
   403‚Üí<details>
   404‚Üí<summary>[Setting] If you want to customize the `noscript` CSS fallback</summary>
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
